<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-733-428  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 733 428.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Design  April 26 1990 v38 n8 p95(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Working with FDDI: a designer's guide; ease of manageability,improvement in throughput, and cost reduction are issues toconsider in FDDI design. (fiber-distributed data interface)(tutorial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Parker, Karen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fiber distributed data interface (FDDI) optical communicationstechnology enables the development of larger, faster local areanetworks (LANs) that are reliable and easy to manage.andP;  The FDDIprotocol standard defined by the ANSI X3T9.5 committee specifies afiber-optic transmission medium, token-access mode, ring topologyand 100M-bit/sec data rate.andP;  The technology will be used toimplement backbone, back-end, and, most frequently, front-endnetworks.andP;  Developing a viable FDDI network requires determininghow end user requirements affect station architecture, embeddingnetwork management capabilities in station hardware, identifyingbottlenecks and optimizing throughput, and optimizing FDDI stationquality while containing costs.andP;  FDDI functionality and each ofthe development requirements are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TutorialMethodsRequirements AnalysisFunctionsImplementationFiber Distributed Data Interface StandardSystem design.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   Use of FDDI in backbone, back-end and front-end applications.andO;(chart)FDDI frame and token format. (table)The data structure incorporates data-unit descriptors and dataunits. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>